author: Misrupt
text:
Dishwasher experiment was botched so hard. First of all this load was an anomaly, even if you dont wash the dishes before putting them in, these were deliberately messy as a test, which is fine, but then you put them all together and the dishwasher is fighting, its gonna take more time because it will go until the last dish is not letting off dirt.

While I agree, 6 hours to wash dishes is ridiculous and you might as well hand wash them (I do), there were so many variables here that were just thrown out the window. You had AB try and "rinse" them after stopping the load short, the dishes were hot and had soap, after you stop it and hand rinse them, they are no longer hot, making food stick again, as well as a completely different pressure of water.

I think this experiment has to be run with multiple loads, some being mostly normal with a few unwashed, some being half and half, and some being all not washed before going in, then you compare the times of each load, as well as how many dishes, what food was on them and where they were located. You need to have some constants between the loads of the same dishes with the same messiness.

Then you could compare the cleanliness of the dishes that were the same based on the difficulty of the wash and the amount. This will give you more accurate results on the dishwashers capabilities as well as its thresholds of its capability to clean certain things.

If you really wanted to test this theory harder, you would try multiple models of dishwashers as well as messing with water pressures, and soaps.

Overall, I was never good at science but if you're going to act so invested about something, at least attempt to do it right.

Edit: Regardless though, imo you should atleast scrape/rinse off food before the dishwasher so you dont get food in there and have to clean that eventually. However, this was a frustrating segment, because even if I am on the other side of it, I still think it needs a fair test, multiple times to really confirm. But I will say if you only eat half of your oatmeal, just scrape the rest into the trash and then put it in the dishwasher.

author: CAO Designworks
text:
The dishwasher didn't add time, the pre-rinse cycle includes a soak time and those don't usually count toward the wash cycle time. At least it doesn't on my dishwasher.
And to add to that, none of the dishes were scraped, which is literally what you're supposed to do. It's one of the first things in the manual. You don't have to pre-rinse, but you can't put a whole meal in the dishwasher. This was never going to work just because of that fact.

Ethan's comment about the screen on the bottom: Food is not supposed to bypass the mesh in any way. The mesh is what allows the water to be reused as it keeps any and all food debris from circulating through the system and clogging up the sprayer nozzles.

This was, quite possibly, the worst way to test the debate, regardless of what side you are on.
However, if this does anything, it really shows you that, despite all of that food, grease, and glue, the dishwasher still managed to get a lot of the debris and food off of the dishes

author: Soft Kitty
text:
You piled bowls full of food into the dishwasher that clogged and overflowed the filter meaning food and dirt got into the system and hosed all over the dishes. That means the propellers inside were probably barely turning and probably so clogged that barely any pressure was reaching the dishes.

This was literally the stupidest test ever because you would not put all that same lose food waste into a sink and wash in that same water - at the very least you'd scraps the lose food off and had you dont that this over flowing would probably not have happened.

There is a very good chance you broke the dishwasher permanently too, because that noise was the pumps propellor grinding on food waste which should never be able to get into that part of the dishwasher, meaning there was no chance the pump was working at full pressure and therefore the washer was never going to clean.

Furthermore I notice you have an expose element in that dishwasher which also means that is the oldest design on the market from over 20 years ago and is not even legal in most countries because it's a literal fire hazard and highly inefficient which means it's very definitely a cheap piece of junk.

Modern dishwashers have internal elements and a much more robust and extensive filtration system which you basically destroyed in that model - this is proved by food being in the motor. And, because modern dishwashers have better filtration systems they should have coped noticeably better, even with your stupidity.

Frankly the test was over the second you put a bowl that was completely full of oatmeal in the machine, it was never going to wash with all of that clogging the filter. No-one would ever do that and it was an invalid test.

No amount of time would have let this dishwasher function properly because you never let it function properly from the outset.

author: Soft Kitty
text:
Dishwashers absolutely can have dirt sensors in them but there are other cheaper less accurate ways for them to determine the load and the soiling.

Your cheap crappy dishwasher almost certainly does not have any water testing sensors as they are only available in both good brands and more expensive models.
And no the cheap crappy ones you listed at $3-500 absolutely do not come with any sensors but timing of fill levels can also indicate wash times without sensors.
You will not find advanced sensors etc in any dishwasher under 7-800 us dollars whatsoever. A good dishwasher is normally over $1500

What your washer undoubtedly has are two much cheaper devices that guide its operation times.

One is a pressure sensor and another is a water level sensor. It's complicated but these two sensors can monitor the fill times and how the pressure changes at what point in the cycle to determine reasonably well how soiled the items are.

After that it adjusts the cycle and the durations of each stage accordingly. Your cycle time is going down very slowly because you put it on a normal cycle which was completely wrong for the dishes you put in there and the machine is trying to accommodate as best it can.

However nothing it does will solve the problem because you already skipped important stages by choosing the wrong load type at the start so it will not clean properly.

author: Dylan Smith
text:
When we hear the claims that it wastes water to pre-rinse, and that the dishwasher can fully clean any dish on a single clean and that it's more energy and water efficient - what we expect from these claims is that when we put the dishwasher on a wash that lasts x amount of time it will fully clean all the dishes in that time without adding extra time, and wasting more water and energy.

The dishwasher clearly failed to do this.

It's clear that the claims that a dishwasher can clean anything in a single wash hinges on the fact that the machine will add time indefinitely until everything is clean. This isn't a fair way to define a "single clean" and it ultimately contradicts the claim that it's more energy and water efficient.

Dishwashers can gtfo, sponge and sink is the way to go

author: audioliciousxxx
text:
Even though I'm on the pre-rinse required team, this was not a fair test.

First of all, to test, should you be putting substances in the dishwasher that we don't normally put in it (ex. Spackle, glue, paint, tape)??

Second, some of those dishes weren't even scraped off into the trash. There was WAY too much food loaded in with those dishes. Of course that shit is gonna clog up the filter and just keep recirculating the same filthy water onto the dishes, never able to clean anything.

Third, the way those dishes were loaded in - some items didn't stand a chance of getting cleaned because of the placement of the loaded up dishes before the cycle was started. Not enough space between things.

That being said, unless you want to be picking filth out of your filter constantly, pre-rinse your damned dishes!! üòÇ

author: Soft Kitty
text:
It's wild to me how badly all of you understand the operations of dishwashers.

A small kitchen sink hold 20 litres of water and you can never wash even half of a full load of dishes from a dishwasher in a sink without changing out the water at least one time.
A dishwasher uses between 9 and 15 litres of water for a full cycle unless it's very cheap and poor quality.

What's more the dishwasher is only heating a tiny fraction of the water it uses overall, whereas all the water in the sink wash is always hot - but importantly never hot enough to sterilise, therefore you are getting an inferior wash in a sink, and the water is not filter through a progressive micro filter so you are always putting dirty water on the dishes in a sink except for the very first items.

The pump in a dishwasher requires very little energy to run and the heating element is a hyper efficient in line water heater, which is dramatically more efficient than a kitchen sink which receives hot water from a central source which is not remotely as efficient as micro heating water to demand.

Also being centralised means the water travels the distance of piping in your home, meaning you waste an average of 4 litres of hot water before you even get hot water to the sink. Thus the dishwasher typically work out using a fraction of the electricity.

I have never heard of this insane theory of having garbage disposals inside dishwasher and I believe that's either delusional, made up, or in so few brands and models it's not even relevant - One thing is certain, it's a monumentally stupid idea, because it's not needed based on the design of dishwashers.
I have certainly never once seen a dishwasher with a garbage disposal, not ever heard of one.

I have heard however that you can attach the outlet hose of the dishwasher to the garbage disposal in the sink which is still not relevant because no large items ever pass the filtration system of a dishwasher - that's why you must clean the filters every single month.

Most importantly a domestic dishwasher absolutely could have washed all those things except the dried glue and paint if it was set for the most heavy duty cycle and allowed to complete, and began the cycle with a clean filter. Except for the fact that you 100% would have clogged all the filters of the appliance and would have needed to clean them out mid cycle because no-one on earth puts a bowl completely full of oatmeal in the dishwasher without at least scraping the excess off it first.

The importance of using the correct cycles in dishwashers, and the correct detergent, and having clean filters cannot be overstated. For example the fastest cycles are essentially just for glassware and very lightly soiled items.

You don't seem capable of grasping this basic concept.

As for commercial dishwashers:

They have a super fast cycle time of approximately 1 minute because - THEY DO NOT WASH DISHES!!!!! - They sterilise the dishes which is required by law. All of the dishwashing in a restaurant is handled by a person and a very high pressure spray hose cleaning the dishes BEFORE they go into the dishwasher.
That's simply how it works.

All a commercial dishwasher is ever doing is a super hot high pressure rinse and sterilise cycle.

Virtually none of what you people are saying about dishwasher is remotely accurate, and this test was incredibly asinine.

author: Soil Punk
text: Ethan is not very informed about GMOs or agriculture and it aggravates me to no end as someone who works in this field to hear him spouting nonsense. You cannot lump the technology of genetic modification into any blanket statement. The goals of various genetic engineering projects are very different. Many such endeavors are furthering a destructive form of agriculture that is destroying the planet all so ag-chem companies can make more money selling their herbicides to farmers. 70% of the money made in agriculture is made by these chemical companies, not farmers, not distributers, not harvesters. Also many pesticides cannot be easily washed off due to the surfactants used to make them adhere to plant surfaces or because they become incorporated into the tissues of the crop. Yes the Organic labeling and regulation system has many deep flaws, Certified Naturally Grown is far superior. There are regenerative agriculture models that successfully grow crops with less inputs and yield crops with greater nutrient density because of it's focus on soil health. I design and consult for these farmers for a living and am currently engaged in multiple grant funded research projects demonstrating support of these claims. I just wish Ethan didn't speak so matter-of-fact about nuanced issues he is far from being an expert on.
